ce:caption.ce:simple-para:
Morphometric analysis on synthesized FPCDsusing adult male and female Artemia sp.
Image 1 Yolk Sac abnormalities;
Image 2 Clear digestive tract with faeces materials.

ce:section.ce:para:
In present ecotoxicological experiments, both male and female Artemia sp. served as test animals to explore the potential ecotoxic effects of FPCDs. Findings revealed that as the concentration of FPCDs escalated, a consistent mortality rate was observed during both 24-h and 72-h exposure period. After 24 h, at 100 μg/ml of FPCDs, mortality peaked at 70% for males and 80% for females. Moreover, within 72-h exposure frame, mortality rates for males varied between 30% and 60%, and for females between 50% and 80%, across concentrations ranging from 10 to 60 μg/ml (Fig. 8
                        ). Nevertheless, the LC50 value predicted through probit analysis for male and female animals are 71.374 and 48.625 μg/ml, respectively (Table 1). These findings suggest that female Artemia are more vulnerable to CDs than their male counterparts (Fig. 9
                        ).
